@page "/open-source/norwx"

<PageTitle>NoRWX Proof-of-Concept - NOSTDLIB</PageTitle>

<Navbar />

<article class="blog-post">
    <div class="container">
        <a href="/#open-source" class="back-link">&larr; Back to Open Source</a>

        <header class="post-header">
            <span class="post-icon">🔒</span>
            <h1>[NoRWX] Proof-of-Concept</h1>
            <div class="post-meta">
                <span class="post-tech mono">x86-64 assembly, C</span>
                <span class="post-status experimental">Experimental</span>
            </div>
            <p class="post-intro">A proof-of-concept demonstrating execution of position-independent x86-64 machine code
                from read/write-only memory without requiring executable permissions, bypassing traditional memory
                protection mechanisms.</p>
        </header>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>Overview</h2>
            <p>
                NoRWX demonstrates a novel technique for running machine code without marking memory as executable.
                Traditional code execution requires RWX (Read-Write-Execute) or at minimum RX permissions on memory
                pages.
                This project proves that with hardware breakpoints and a custom instruction emulator, code can execute
                from RW-only memory regions.
            </p>
            <p>
                The technique avoids traditional memory protection changes like <code>VirtualProtect</code>, making it
                an interesting research vector for understanding CPU execution models and security boundaries.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>Core Features</h2>
            <div class="features-grid">
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>No Executable Memory</h3>
                    <p>Stores and runs machine code in RW-only memory regions</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Hardware Breakpoints</h3>
                    <p>Uses DR0/DR7 debug registers to trigger instruction handling</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Custom Emulator</h3>
                    <p>Full x86-64 instruction emulator for arithmetic, logic, control flow, and stack operations</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Windows API Support</h3>
                    <p>Enables Windows API calls from within emulated code</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>How It Works</h2>
            <p>The mechanism relies on four key steps:</p>
            <div class="structure-grid">
                <div class="structure-item">
                    <h4>1. Code Placement</h4>
                    <p>Position-independent machine code is placed in RW-only memory</p>
                </div>
                <div class="structure-item">
                    <h4>2. Breakpoint Installation</h4>
                    <p>Hardware breakpoint is set on the entry address using debug registers</p>
                </div>
                <div class="structure-item">
                    <h4>3. VEH Registration</h4>
                    <p>Vectored Exception Handler is registered to intercept breakpoint exceptions</p>
                </div>
                <div class="structure-item">
                    <h4>4. Instruction Emulation</h4>
                    <p>Handler reads, decodes, and emulates each instruction, then reinstalls breakpoint at next address
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>Technical Components</h2>
            <ul class="requirements-list">
                <li><strong>Instruction Emulator</strong> - Supports arithmetic, logic, control flow, stack, and
                    miscellaneous x86-64 operations</li>
                <li><strong>Vectored Exception Handler</strong> - Manages hardware breakpoints and dispatches to
                    emulator</li>
                <li><strong>Register/Flag Management</strong> - Updates thread context registers and CPU flags after
                    each instruction</li>
                <li><strong>Program Loader</strong> - Loads binary code blobs and orchestrates the execution flow</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>Emulator Capabilities</h2>
            <p>The x86-64 emulator handles the following instruction categories:</p>
            <div class="features-grid">
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Arithmetic</h3>
                    <p>ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, INC, DEC, NEG, CMP</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Logic</h3>
                    <p>AND, OR, XOR, NOT, SHL, SHR, SAR, ROL, ROR</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Control Flow</h3>
                    <p>JMP, Jcc (conditional jumps), CALL, RET, LOOP</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-item">
                    <h3>Stack & Memory</h3>
                    <p>PUSH, POP, MOV, LEA, XCHG</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>Execution Model</h2>
            <pre class="code-block"><code>┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  RW Memory (Non-Executable)                             │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │  PIC Machine Code Blob                          │    │
│  │  [instruction bytes...]                         │    │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                          │
                          ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Hardware Breakpoint (DR0) triggers on entry            │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                          │
                          ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  VEH intercepts EXCEPTION_SINGLE_STEP                   │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │  1. Read instruction bytes from RW memory       │    │
│  │  2. Decode and emulate instruction              │    │
│  │  3. Update registers and flags                  │    │
│  │  4. Set breakpoint on next instruction          │    │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
            <h2>Use Cases</h2>
            <ul class="requirements-list">
                <li>Security research and understanding execution models</li>
                <li>Studying hardware breakpoint mechanisms</li>
                <li>Exploring alternative code execution techniques</li>
                <li>Educational purposes for low-level programming</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section limitations">
            <h2>Important Notice</h2>
            <ul class="limitations-list">
                <li>This is research-only code for educational purposes</li>
                <li>Do not use to evade detection or run untrusted code</li>
                <li>Do not use to break laws or policies</li>
                <li>Performance is significantly slower than native execution due to emulation overhead</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section post-footer">
            <h2>Source Code</h2>
            <p>The project is open source and available for security researchers and low-level programmers interested in
                understanding x86-64 execution models.</p>
